DUKKAHA dry Egyptian condiment made up of a blend of nuts, seeds, herbs and spices which is enjoyed at breakfast with bread dipped in olive oil, or as a snack.There are many different recipes for dukkah; this is a basic one to which ground cinnamon and dried mint or marjoram are added.</img>Dukkah. Image: iStockDukkah. Image: iStockIngredients:250ml (1 cup) hazelnuts, peeled85ml (1/3 cup) sesame seeds30-45ml (2-3 tbsp) coriander seeds30-45ml (2-3 tbsp) cumin seeds30ml (2 tbsp) dried mint or dried marjoram5ml (1 tsp) freshly ground black pepper5ml (1 tsp) good quality saltMethod:1) Place the nuts and seeds on a dry baking tray and roast in a preheated oven at 180 C for 5 minutes until toasted and aromatic, taking care not to burn them. 2) Combine the toasted nuts and seeds with the mint, salt and pepper in a food processor and blend till just crushed, but not pulverised - it s meant to be a dry blend. 3) Cool and store in an airtight container.BERBEREFiery and aromatic, Ethiopian berbere is a deep red blend of spices. Ingredients:5ml (1 tsp) ground ginger2,5ml ( tsp) ground cardamom2,5ml ( tsp) ground coriander2,5ml ( tsp) ground fenugreek seeds2,5ml ( tsp) ground nutmegPinch of ground clovesPinch of ground cinnamonPinch of ground allspice30ml (2 tbsp) salt250ml (1 cup) fresh cayenne pepper125ml ( cup) paprika5ml (1 tsp) freshly ground black pepperMethod:1) In a heavy-based dry saucepan toast the ginger, cardamom, coriander, fenugreek, nutmeg, cloves, cinnamon and allspice. Shake or stir to prevent burning.2) Add the salt, cayenne pepper, paprika and pepper and continue toasting and stirring for 10-15 minutes.3) Cool and store in a glass jar with a lid. This will keep in the fridge for 6 months.CHERMOULAThis North African marinade is particularly good with fish, lamb or chicken.</img>Chermoula. Image: iStockChermoula. Image: iStockIngredients:1 bunch of fresh coriander, finely chopped4 cloves of garlic, finely chopped15ml (1 tbsp) smoked paprika15ml (1 tbsp) ground cumin5ml (1 tsp) salt5ml (1 tsp) ground ginger1 red chilli, seeded and chopped60ml (4 tbsp) olive oil15ml (1 tbsp) preserved lemon*, pith removed and chopped Method:1) Combine all the ingredients together in a blender or food processor and blend till you have a paste.*Don't have preserved lemons? Use the finely grated rind and juice of 1 small lemon instead. Roasted Harissa prawns with tomatoes, baby marrows & mushroomsHARISSA PASTEA hot, aromatic North African blend of dried red chillies, garlic, salt, coriander, cumin and fennel seeds and olive oil.Ingredients:60ml (4 tbsp) coriander seeds60ml (4 tbsp) cumin seeds60ml (4 tbsp) fennel seeds20 cloves of garlic1 large red onion, peeled and chopped20 red chillies, seeded and chopped (use gloves)1 large red pepper, grilled, peeled, seeded and chopped125ml olive oil15ml (1 tbsp) saltMethod:1) In a large heavy-based dry pan toast the coriander, cumin and fennel seeds until fragrant, stirring all the time and taking care they don t burn. Tip into a spice blender and grind till you have a fine powder. Set aside.2) In a food processor, combine the garlic, onion, chillies, pepper and olive oil and blend till you have a paste.3) Tip the paste into a pan and cook over a very gentle heat, stirring from time to time, till thickened. Stir in the spices and add the salt, then remove from the heat.4) Store in a sterilised jar with a lid in the fridge for 2-3 weeks. Asha's Spice Box: Ras el hanout fish stewRAS EL HANOUTCharacterised by the large number of spices, anything form 12-30, ras el hanout can be used in savoury and sweet dishes. Use the freshest spices to allow the flavour of each to stand out.Ingredients:7,5ml (1 tsp) sugar7,5ml (1 tsp) paprika7,5ml (1 tsp) freshly ground black pepper5ml (1 tsp) cayenne pepper5ml (1 tsp) ground cardamom5ml (1 tsp) ground allspicePinch of dried cloves10ml (2 tsp) ground nutmeg10ml (2 tsp) ground coriander10ml (2 tsp) ground cumin10ml (2 tsp) ground ginger10ml (2 tsp) ground turmeric10ml (2 tsp) salt10ml (2 tsp) ground cinnamonMethod:1) Combine all the ingredients in a large heavy-based dry pan and toast over a low heat, stirring continuously, until warm and fragrant. Take care not to burn them.2) Allow to cool and store in a glass jar with a lid. To retain the flavour, store the spice mix in the freezer if you don t use it within a month. Look out for five delicious recipes that make the most of these aromatic spice blends, pastes and marinades in the Sunday Times on Sunday, April 10 2016.